{<b>HE WHO KNOWS, GOES</b>You <b>KNOW</b> your side has 26-28 points. You <b>KNOW</b> your side has 8 or more \Ss. You <b>GO</b> to 4\S.

South plays 4\S. West leads the \DJ.

<b>South plays 4\S. West leads the \DJ.</b>

Losers: \S 2/3 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = 3/4

You are definitely going to lose the \DA and the \S A K. Therefore you must plan to avoid losing a third \S.

You should lead <b>UP TO</b> your honor cards. Cover the \DJ and lose to East's \DA. Win his return (probably another \D) in dummy. Lead a small \S to your \SJ. West wins with an honor and probably plays the \D10. Ruff it, lead a \C to dummy and lead the last \S. If East plays the other high honor you play low. If East plays low you guess whether to play the \SK, or \ST. Your best play is to assume the two honors were split and play the \SQ.

Leading twice toward the \S Q J gives you a guarantee on this layout because East held a doubleton high honor.

Now  

Here West has taken your \SJ with the \SA. When you again lead a small \S from dummy say that East plays the \S5.

 You might think that West is just as likely to have held an original doubleton \S A K as doubleton \S A 10, and that playing the \S9 would be as good a play as \SQ.

This is untrue for a very classy-named reason - <b>The Principle of Restricted Choice</b>. You may not even believe it when you read it, but it's mathematically sound. If West were dealt an original \S A K, he would have been just as likely to win with the \SK as with the \SA. The fact that he actually won the \SA makes it less likely that he also holds the \SK.}
[Play "W"]DJ

